I_kwDOK3SaHs6k_zHv.body:
Is it just me or anyone else thinks the logger has a serious problem. It mutates an object passed to it. 

In simple words, any object you pass to it, doesn't remain the same object anymore.  This has a potential to introduce hard to debug problems in the future. Logger is a cross cutting concern and it is going to get into all repositories and introduce this problem. The author itself was not sure about it either. This is the mutating function in logger.  It mutates `Metadata`. I am not sure if it has some other mutating functions too.

```typescript
  private _addDiagnosticInformation(metadata?: Metadata) {
    // this is a utility function to get the name of the function that called the log
    // I have mixed feelings on this because it manipulates metadata later possibly without the developer understanding why and where,
    // but seems useful for the metadata parser to understand where the comment originated from

    if (!metadata) {
      metadata = {};
    } else if (typeof metadata !== "object") {
      metadata = { message: metadata };
    }

    const stackLines = new Error().stack?.split("\n") || [];
    if (stackLines.length > 3) {
      const callerLine = stackLines[3];
      const match = callerLine.match(/at (\S+)/);
      if (match) {
        metadata.caller = match[1];
      }
    }

    return metadata;
  }
```

This problem has already penetrated to many other repositories now because tests in those repositories are expecting these mutations by logger. If you make it immutable now, those tests will start to fail. But I still think it is a good idea to make it immutable.

If you don't know, it was state mutation that used cause those "Have you tried restarting it?" solutions. If every other function starts to mutate objects at its own will, objects get into strange states and restarting the system often becomes to be only quick solution. 


